🧪 Network Forensics using Wireshark — Steps

STEP 1: Open Wireshark
• Open terminal in Kali Linux
• Run: wireshark &

STEP 2: Select Network Interface
• Wireshark opens
• Select interface (eth0 / wlan0)
• Click Start (shark icon)
• Packet capture begins

STEP 3: Generate Traffic
• Open browser
• Visit any site (Google, YouTube)
• Packets start appearing

STEP 4: Apply Protocol Filters
• Type in filter bar:
• tcp → TCP packets
• udp → UDP packets
• http → HTTP packets

STEP 5: Filter by IP Address
• Use: ip.addr == 192.168.x.x
• Shows traffic of that IP

STEP 6: Filter by Source IP
• Use: ip.src == 192.168.x.x
• Shows packets from source

STEP 7: Follow TCP Stream
• Right-click TCP packet
• Follow → TCP Stream
• View full communication

STEP 8: Detect Suspicious Traffic (Port Scan)
• Open terminal
• Run: nmap -sS 192.168.x.x
• In filter: tcp.flags.syn == 1 && tcp.flags.ack == 0
• Observe multiple SYN packets
• Indicates port scanning

STEP 9: Capture File Properties
• Statistics → Capture File Properties
• View packets, size, duration

STEP 10: Resolved Addresses
• Statistics → Resolved Addresses
• Shows IP ↔ domain, MAC ↔ device

STEP 11: Protocol Hierarchy
• Statistics → Protocol Hierarchy
• Shows protocol usage

STEP 12: Conversations
• Statistics → Conversations
• Shows device communication

STEP 13: Packet Length
• Statistics → Packet Length
• Shows packet size distribution

STEP 14: Endpoints
• Statistics → Endpoints
• Shows all devices

STEP 15: I/O Graphs
• Statistics → I/O Graphs
• Shows traffic over time
